<BaseLayout
  title="Download your Section 75 Claim Pack"
  description="Thank you for purchasing the Section 75 Claim Pack. Your download is ready."
>
  <article class="prose prose-gray max-w-none">

    <h1>Your claim pack is ready to download</h1>

    <p>
      Thank you for your purchase. The Section 75 Claim Pack is a single PDF containing nine documents. Download it now and save it somewhere you can find it again — you may need it over the coming weeks as your claim progresses.
    </p>

    <div class="not-prose my-8">
      <a
        href="/downloads/section-75-claim-pack.pdf"
        download
        class="btn-primary"
      >
        Download the claim pack (PDF)
      </a>
    </div>

    <h2>What is in the pack</h2>

    <p>The PDF contains nine documents in the following order:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Cover sheet and decision guide</strong> — a one-page table showing which documents to use and in what order, depending on your situation.</li>
      <li><strong>Initial claim letter</strong> — a formal letter to your credit card provider's disputes team, citing Section 75(1) of the Consumer Credit Act 1974. Covers non-delivery, faulty goods, goods not as described, and business failure scenarios.</li>
      <li><strong>Evidence cover letter</strong> — a structured letter to accompany the documents you send to your bank, with a table for itemising each piece of evidence.</li>
      <li><strong>Process guide</strong> — a one-page reference covering the claim timeline, what the bank is required to do under FCA rules, and when to escalate.</li>
      <li><strong>Rejection rebuttal (standard)</strong> — a response to common rejection reasons: insufficient evidence, not covered by Section 75, no explanation given.</li>
      <li><strong>Rejection rebuttal (overseas purchase)</strong> — for cases where the bank claims Section 75 does not apply because the supplier was overseas. Cites OFT v Lloyds TSB Bank plc [2007] UKHL 48.</li>
      <li><strong>Rejection rebuttal (part payment on card)</strong> — for cases where the bank claims it is only liable for the amount charged to the card, rather than the full contract value.</li>
      <li><strong>Rejection rebuttal (third party or booking agent)</strong> — for cases where the bank claims Section 75 does not apply because you paid an intermediary rather than the ultimate supplier.</li>
      <li><strong>Financial Ombudsman Service complaint letter</strong> — a formal complaint to the FOS for use if the bank issues a final rejection or fails to respond within eight weeks.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      Each document begins with a short note explaining when to use it. Placeholder text — the details you need to fill in — is marked in bold and in square brackets throughout.
    </p>

    <h2>Where to start</h2>

    <p>
      If you have not yet written to your bank, start with Document 2 (the initial claim letter). Read Document 1 first to confirm which version of the letter applies to your situation.
    </p>

    <p>
      If your bank has already rejected your claim, go directly to Documents 5 through 8 and select the rebuttal that matches the reason they gave. If you are unsure which applies, the <a href="/guide/">complete Section 75 guide</a> covers the most common rejection grounds and the correct response to each.
    </p>

    <h2>Problems with the download?</h2>

    <p>
      If the file did not download or you cannot open it, <a href="/contact/">contact us</a> and we will help you access it. Please include the email address you used for payment.
    </p>

  </article>
</BaseLayout>
